messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full path
- /posts/{post}/likes

All methods acceptable?
- false

Methods accepted (based on the route declarations in the code)
- HEAD: false
- POST: true
- OPTIONS: false
- TRACE: false
- GET: false
- PUT: false
- DELETE: true
- PATCH: false

Explanation
- In routes/auth.php there is an explicit POST route that maps to the store method on App\Http\Controllers\PostLikeController:
  Route::post('/posts/{post}/likes', [PostLikeController::class, 'store'])->name('posts.likes.store');
  This yields the path /posts/{post}/likes and makes POST accepted by the endpoint implemented in app/Http/Controllers/PostLikeController::store.
- The same file also registers a DELETE route for the identical path that maps to the controller's destroy method:
  Route::delete('/posts/{post}/likes', [PostLikeController::class, 'destroy'])->name('posts.likes.destroy');
  This makes DELETE accepted at the same path (handled by destroy).
- No other HTTP methods are declared for that path in the provided route files. Per the instructions, I did not assume framework behavior (automatic HEAD/OPTIONS handling); only methods explicitly declared in the code are considered acceptable.
- Note: routes/api.php also declares a POST and DELETE for /v1/posts/{post}/likes, but those map to App\Http\Controllers\Api\V1\PostLikeController (a different controller namespace). Those are separate endpoints (/v1/...); they do not change the mapping for App\Http\Controllers\PostLikeController in routes/auth.php.
